# TDD Strategy

Follow Red-Green-Refactor for feature and bug-fix work unless I explicitly ask otherwise.

## Red
- Start by writing or updating tests to define expected behavior first.
- Prefer module test conventions already used in the repo (NUnit, fixture pattern, assertion extensions).
- If dependencies/handlers are missing, keep tests as explicit red-phase failures (do not skip silently).

## Green
- Implement the minimum production code needed to satisfy failing tests.
- Keep changes scoped to what tests require; avoid unrelated refactors in this step.

## Refactor
- Improve naming/structure only after tests pass.
- Preserve behavior and keep tests green.

## Execution and Validation
- Run targeted tests for changed scope first, then broader build/test only if needed.
- In status updates, state which phase we are in: Red, Green, or Refactor.

## Assertion Style
- Prefer assertion extension helpers for DTO/domain comparisons where module patterns exist.
- For DTO assertions, validate top-level properties and nested collections/items explicitly.
